value.value: The uptake of food ranging from small particles to live invertebrates.

A mode of feeding by females, in which the fascicle is deployed beyond the labella to penetrate the skin of the host, and a large volume of blood is imbibed and passed into the midgut. Blood feeding can be divided into four phases.
Is the removal of particles suspended in the water column or associated with the water surface.
Is the removal and ingestion of the biofilm that abheres tightly to submerged plant and mineral surfaces, and also of the algae and stalked protists that adhere directly to such surfaces.

definition.value: Larvae of Aedes exhibit this feeding mode in rock pools and it is probably more widespread.

value.value: The gnawing and biting-off of small fragments of tissue, whether from plantsor dead invertebrates.

definition.value: Gnawing of leaves has been described in Culiseta inornata and Aedes triseriatus larvae. Culex bitaeniorhynchus larvae feed selectively on filamentous chlorophytes. Tripteroides use the shredding feeding mode and feed on dead invertebrates.

value.value: Is the resuspension and removal of particles deposited on or loosely attached to surfaces.

definition.value: It is found in many species of Aedes and in some species of Psorophora, Haemagogus and Wyeomyia.

value.value: Some mosquito larvae seize and engulf other insects, and often of their own size. The prey is swallowed whole.

definition.value: Is observed in larvae of Toxorhynchites and of the subgenera Lutzia (of Culex), Mucidus (of Aedes) and Psorophora. Also larvae of a number of sebatine genera are facultative predators, as are larvae of Eretmapodites.

value.value: Mosquito larvae imbibe substantial volumes of water when feeding and also drink extensively in the absence of food.
Declining flow rate of urine production.
Very rapid flow in the first minutes after the blood meal.
When the flow rate is slightly above the control level.
Mosquito larvae pass through four instars. Growth is continuous throughout each instar, as can be seen in the progressive increase in size of the body regions that are covered with thin cuticle.

definition.value: The heavily sclerotized parts of the body, the cranium and respiratory siphon , increase in size immediately after ecdysis but this is a manifestation of earlier growth processes. Growth of the soft parts is not always isometric.

value.value: Mosquito larvae pass through four instar. Each instar is a stage of development but also growth.
The retraction of the epidermis from the cuticle.
The final stage of moulting. Shedding of what remains of the old cuticle.
The ecdysis between any of the four larval instars.

definition.value: The epidermis can be seen to separate from the cuticle and to secrete new cuticle and bristles beneath it while the tracheal epithelium similarly retracts from the tracheal linings and secretes new cuticular lining around them. A mid-ventral ecdysial line is also found in many species. Movements of the head free it from the old cranium and the dorsal split extends back over the thorax so the peristaltic movements the larva is able to escape from the cast cuticle, sometimes in less than a minute. The old tracheal trunks have broken across just behind their connections to the non-functional spiracles in each segment.

value.value: The ecdysis between the larval and the pupal stage.

definition.value: This ecdysis is heralded by the appereance of the respiratory trumpets and palmate float setae of the pharate pupa as dark bodies beneath the larval cuticle. The larval trachea collapse at this time. The larval cuticle and tracheal linings are shed much as at previous ecdyses, and during this period the labial and maxillary palp disks are extruded from the peripodial cavities.

value.value: The emergence of the adult mosquito from the pupal cuticle.

The rudiments of some imaginal disks are present in newly hatched larvae and develop slowly during the larval stage; others appear as late as the 3rd instar. Each imaginal disk is first apparent as a plate of columnar epidermal cells which grows slowly with cell division. Increase in size of the imaginal disks occurs principally during the 4th instar, accompanied by numerous mitoses, and in most cases the disks are shaped only very approximately like the adult appendages at the time.
The development and differentiation of the gonads and primary sexual characters.

label.value: development of the central nervous system

value.value: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the central nervous system over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The central nervous system is the core nervous system that serves an integrating and coordinating function. In vertebrates it consists of the brain, spinal cord and spinal nerves. In those invertebrates with a central nervous system it typically consists of a brain, cerebral ganglia and a nerve cord.

The development of the compound eyes proceeds in a sequence of events - first determination and cellular proliferation, then differentiation - which pass as waves across a region of the head epidermis, the 'prospective eye field', that will transform into the compound eye.

At metamorphosis some of the tissues that have endopolyploid nuclei undergo somatic reduction and cell divistion to yield a large number of small, apparently de-differentiated cells which are competent to form adult tissues.

label.value: response of single-walled multiporous hair sensilla

value.value: They are sensitive to olfactory stimuli and occur abundantly on the antennal flagella. The hairs are pointed or blunt and arise without sockets.

definition.value: Most experimental work has been undertaken on Aedes aegypti, in which four distinct types of single-walled multiporous hair sensilla have been distinguished.

label.value: responses of short blunt single-walled multiporous hair sensilla

value.value: When these sensilla are exposed to stimulating vapours, the excited neurones gave a phasic-tonic response. It seems likely that the short blunt single-walled multiporous hair sensila on female antennae are used in the location of oviposition sites.

label.value: responses of short pointed single-walled multiporous hair sensilla

value.value: These sensilla are stimulated by saturated C3 to C7 fatty acids at unspesific dosage rates. They respond also to ethyl propanoate.

label.value: responses of long pointed single-walled multiporous hair sensilla

value.value: These seensilla were perdominantly stimulated by C2 to C10 saturated straight-chain fatty acids. Their spontaneous activity was inhibited by volatile oils.

label.value: responses of blunt single-walled multiporous hair sensilla

value.value: These sensilla give mixed responses to fatty acids and volatile oils. Individual neurones within particular classes of sensilla appeared to have shown different sensitivity spectra to the range of carboxylic acids tested. Also the pattern of information provided by these cells could be intergrated to allow refined discrimination of fatty acid odours.

label.value: response of single-walled multiporous peg sensilla

value.value: The pegs, which arise from shallow depressions in the integument, are usually club-shaped but sometimes finger shaped. They are sensitive to olfactory stimuli.

Electrophysiological studies with extracellular electrodes (on female Aedes aegypti) showed that the neurone producing the largest action potentials was the only one sensitive to carbon dioxide. CO2-sensitive neurones were silent in air without CO2, and had response thresholds between 150 and 300 ppm.

definition.value: Similar responses were obtained with male Aedes aegypti and with females of Aedes taeniorhynchys, Culex quinquefasciatus, Culiseta melanura and Anopheles stephensi.

value.value: The neuron with the smallest spike height is sensitive to octenol. This neurone produces bursts of action potentials upon exposure of a sensillum to 2 s pulses of CO2-free air that had passed through a stimulus cartidge containing solutions of 1-octen-3-ol in mineral oil. The sensitivity of the mosquito neurones to 1-octen-3-ol was said to be equivalent to that of lepidopteran sensory neurones to pheromones when tested by similar protocols for stimulus preparation and delivery.

label.value: response of double-walled multiporous peg sensilla

value.value: The grooved peg sensilla of Aedes aegypti contain from two to five neurones, usually three. Spike analysis of extracellular recordings from grooved peg sensilla of Aedes epactius revealed spontaneous action potentials of three distinct amplitudes.

When exposed to lactic acid vapour, the grooved peg sensilla of Aedes aegypti exhibited one of three firing patterns: (i) a phasic-tonic increase in spike frequency; (ii) a tonic decrease in the frequency of spontaneous spikes; or (iii) no change in spike frequency. Thus neurones are excited or inhibited or are non-responsive.

Electrophysiological evidence from different insects suggests that hygrosensory neurons occur in poreless sensilla. It is thought that absorption of water vapour by the cuticular wall results in deformation of the sensillum.

definition.value: The neurones that were examined (Kellog 1970) are not hygrosensory but were moisture-dependent, losing sensitivity at lower humidities. Kellog also was not working with double-walled multiporous sensilla.

value.value: The reception of the physical stimuli is typically a three-stage process of coupling, transduction and encoding. Is made by the mosquito antennae, which are sensitive to a band of vibrational frequencies, pressure changes or displacements of air particles.
Mechanical deformation of the dendritic membrane, producing receptor potentials.

definition.value:
Most electrophysiological studies of sound reception have been undertaken with sharpened metal electrodes inserted into Johnston's organ.
The receptors potentials that are elicited in Johnston's organ by vibration of the antennal flagellum, when recorded via an extracellular electrode, are sinusoidal in form but occur at twice the frequency of the acoustic stimulus. This phenomenon has been termed frequency doubling.

value.value: Is the conversion of receptor potentials to action potentials, which are beleived to arise in the cell membrane of the sensory neurone close to the junction between the cell body and axon.

label.value: responses of the visual pigments and the chromophores

value.value: Conjugated proteins which are integral constituents of the membranes of photoreceptor organelles. Each consists of a chromophore and a apoprotein to which it is covalently linked. A number of different visual pigments are known from insect eyes.
When the chromophore is in the 11-cis configuration, the principal absorption peak of different visual pigments may appear anywhere in the spectrum between ultraviolet and yellow.

When the chromophore is in the all-trans configuration, and the visual pigment is in the meta-state,the absorption peak appears within a much narrower range, usually in the blue but in higher Diptera in the orange.

The spectral sensitivity of a photoreceptor is determined by the absorption characteristics of its visual pigments. The eyes of different insects contain from one to four receptor types with distinct spectral sensitivities. Mosquito larvae exhibit a negative phototactic or diving response when first exposed to light at night or to a bright source by day, but this is soon followed by a return to the surface.
A compound eye with no separation between the crystalline-cone layer and the retinula, each rhabdom receiving light only from its own corneal lens.
A compound eye in which a clear space is interposed between the dioptric apparatus and the retinula, and light from several corneal lenses falls on each rhabdom, producing a much brighter image.
A compound eye in certain diptera in which the rhabdomeres act as independent light guides.

For an eye to be capable of resolving fine detail, the angular separation between the receptors must be small. Therefore, in compound eyes the smaller the angle between the optical axes of two adjacent ommatidia, the greater the potential of the eye to resolve detail. The interommatidial angle can be measured in a number of ways.
The sensitivity (S) of an eye is a measure of the size of the photon sample that it can capture from each direction.

label.value: minimum resolvable angle of an eye

value.value: For an eye for a grating (not for a point) is twice the interommatidial angle.
Is the highest spatial frequency that an eye can resolve.

definition.value: The acuity of an eye is governed by its spatial frequency only if the quality of its optics is not limited by other structural or environmental factors.

value.value: The angular sensitivity of an ommatidium is determined by three parameters: (i) optical blurring by the lens; (ii) the width of the rhabdom tip; nad (iii) the waveguide properties of the rhabdom.
The half-width of the Airy disc and the half-width of the rhabdom acceptance function combine to give the half-width of the ommatidial acceptance angle.
